              help you. Does carrying out a task&#x2F; activity exhaust you afterwords?</li>
            <li>Equally, don&#x2019;t pretend things are worse than they really are. Knowingly giving false answers as part of a benefit application is benefit fraud, which is a criminal offence.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h2><button aria-controls="the-form" aria-expanded="false">Tips for completing the form</button></h2>
        <div id="the-form" aria-hidden="true">
          <p>When filling out the form:</p>
          <ul class="ticks">
            <li>Don&#x2019;t be intimidated by the questions, or by the form&#x2019;s length. The questions are simple and are not trying to catch you out</li>
            <li>Give enough detail about how your condition affects you</li>
            <li>Get help if you need it from a Citizen&#x2019;s Advice Bureau or advice centre</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h2><button aria-controls="at-the-assessment" aria-expanded="false">Tips at the assessment</button></h2>
        <div id="at-the-assessment" aria-hidden="true">
          <p>At the assessment:</p>
          <ul class="ticks">
            <li>If you are not sure about what you are being asked, ask the assessor for an explanation.</li>
            <li>Take your time to answer questions.</li>
            <li>If you are asked to do something physical such as bend/stretch and it causes you any difficulty or pain or you can't do it, then tell the assessor.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h2><button aria-controls="before" aria-expanded="false">Preparing for the assessment</button></h2>
        <div id="before" aria-hidden="true">
          <ul class="ticks">
            <li>Make a list of your health conditions and disabilities, so that you don&#x2019;t forget to mention them at the assessment</li>
            <li>Think about the ways they impact on the daily living and mobility activities the assessment looks at</li>
            <li>Try <a href="javascript:void(0)" data-action="start-or-resume">practising the assessment</a> on our website first, where you can save and print off your most important answers!</li>
            <li>Plan your journey to the assessment centre in advance. Don&#x2019;t be late!</li>
            <li>Your assessor will probably ask you how you got to the assesment. It may affect your claim if the answer you give seems to contradict the answers given on your form.</li>
            <li>If your condition has worsened since you completed the form, get a report/ letter from a doctor or other professional to explain how it has changed, and how that impacts on you.</li>
            <li>Consider keeping a diary which you can show the assessor. This will help you track your good and bad days, the impact of any treatment you have, and whether what you do on one day affects what you do on the next.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h2><button aria-controls="rights" aria-expanded="false">Your rights</button></h2>
        <div id="rights" aria-hidden="true">
          <ul class="ticks">
            <li>You will be able to claim back reasonable expenses for getting to your assessment, so keep any bus or train tickets, or parking fees.</li>
            <li>You have the right to be accompanied at your assessment. You can ask a relative, friend, carer, or an advocate or support worker to go with you</li>
            <li>You have a right to complain about the assessment if you don&#x2019;t think it was conducted fairly</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h2><button aria-controls="the-outcome" aria-expanded="false">The outcome</button></h2>
        <div id="the-outcome" aria-hidden="true">
          <p>You will receive a letter from the DWP telling you the outcome of your application. It will explain how the decision was made, and include the points you scored in your test. It will tell you which of the components you will get, which rates
            you will receive, and how long it will be until your case will be reassessed.</p>
          <p>Depending on the components and rate of PIP you are entitled to, you might qualify for other benefits or help, for example the motability scheme.</p>
          <p>If you are unhappy with the decision you have received, you can request a mandatory reconsideration. If, after that, you are still unhappy with the decision, you can appeal against it. We recommend that you get some support for this from a local
            Citizen&#x2019;s Advice Bureau or advice centre.</p>
        </div>
